{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nR1 (asserted-capability grounding probe) edits the Pass-1 finder rubric, so it changes what\nEVERY plan review surfaces â€” not a niche path. Before R1 (or any gate candidate, e.g. R5's\nverifier change) is exposed to production, we must measure how much it perturbs the verdicts of\nplans that already passed the gate and closed without trouble. E3 is the counterfactual replay\nthat produces that measurement; with E2 (seeded-defect benchmark) it is the evidence R1 is gated\non.\n\nThe gate this feeds has a hard false-positive bar. Per `docs/research/task-decomposition-sota-2026.md`\nÂ§5 / R1 (lines ~163-169), R1 FAILs if, on **30 sampled historical plans that PASSed and closed with\nzero post-claim edits**, **>3/30 (10%)** gain a new *blocking* finding, or the **median new-advisory\ncount rises by >1 per review**. The epic additionally reports a corroborating aggregate: the\n**PASSâ†’BLOCK flip rate â‰¤2%** on the wider cleanly-closed sample.\n\n**Two confounds this design must remove (both verified in code):**\n\n1. **Recall contamination.** `review_plan` re-surfaces the ticket's OWN prior-review findings as\n   Pass-2 recall candidates via `sidecar.prior_concerns(ctx.ticket_id, repo_root=ctx.tickets_root)`\n   (`pass1.py:504`). `emit_sidecar=False` does NOT disable this READ. A naive fresh candidate replay\n   would therefore see the ticket's entire persisted review history â€” a signal the frozen historical\n   baseline was itself computed under, but which a \"fresh\" run reproduces differently. It must be\n   controlled, not left in.\n2. **Baseline drift + LLM nondeterminism.** The persisted sidecar baseline was produced at a\n   historical SHA, under its own recall, at the gate's default (non-zero) temperature. Comparing a\n   fresh candidate run against it conflates the candidate's effect with those differences.\n\nBecause R-candidates change what Pass-1 *surfaces* (finder-prompt edits), a scoring-only replay over\nthe persisted sidecar findings cannot measure them â€” the candidate side must be a full pipeline\nre-run. Given that, the design splits into two tiers so LLM spend is spent where rigor is required\n(the R1 gate), not everywhere:\n\n- **Coarse tier (~200 tickets, descriptive):** persisted-sidecar baseline vs one fresh\n  recall-stripped candidate run â†’ the transition matrix + the â‰¤2% flip rate, published WITH an\n  explicit recall/nondeterminism caveat (the baseline carried recall the candidate run does not).\n- **Precise tier (30-plan FP-control, the R1 gate):** replay BOTH the current/main gate AND the\n  candidate gate FRESH over the same recall-stripped clones and compare **candidate-vs-current**. This\n  removes both confounds. It roughly DOUBLES LLM cost on the 30 plans (both gates, Ã—N replays) â€” an\n  honest cost, confined to the 30 plans that actually decide R1.\n\n## What\n\n**Definitions (pinned).**\n\n1. **Cleanly-closed ticket** â€” an explicit filter over `outcome_corpus.jsonl` (628 rows; schema in\n   `runs/README.md:53-88`), verified field names:\n   `post_claim_edit_class == \"none\"` **AND** `reopen_count == 0` **AND** `force_close == false`. Encoded\n   in the driver. `post_claim_edit_class == \"none\"` is load-bearing: it removes the ~8.3% post-claim\n   plan-text drift (README Â§5.2) that would otherwise inflate spurious flips.\n\n2. **Baseline verdict source (coarse tier).** The corpus has no verdict field; the baseline is the\n   persisted `REVIEW_RESULT` sidecar, read via\n   `rebar.llm.plan_review.sidecar.all_review_results(tid)` (returns every retained round\n   newestâ†’oldest). Per ticket the baseline is **one round**: the **most-recent round whose\n   `impact_model_version == \"plan-v3\"`** (= `sidecar.IMPACT_MODEL_VERSION`) **and `verdict âˆˆ\n   {PASS,BLOCK}`**. From it we read `verdict` (sidecar.py:482), `material_fingerprint`, `model`, and\n   `findings[]` filtered by `sidecar.surfaced_findings` (`decision âˆˆ {\"block\",\"advisory\"}`). One round\n   (not a cross-round union) keeps verdict/findings/material mutually consistent. Fixing the cohort to\n   `plan-v3` satisfies ADR 0036 (never pool across `impact_model_version`); the driver asserts the\n   candidate build's `sidecar.IMPACT_MODEL_VERSION` equals this cohort version and fails loud\n   otherwise. Frozen (step 0) to `runs/e3/baseline.jsonl` **before any candidate run**, so all\n   comparison reads a committed, immutable file.\n\n3. **Recall-stripped clone (both tiers).** Every FRESH gate run (candidate, and â€” precise tier â€” the\n   current/main gate) runs over a clone of the ticket store with recall neutralized, mirroring E2's\n   isolation: copy `REAL_REPO/.tickets-tracker` â†’ a tmp store, then **delete every\n   `*-REVIEW_RESULT.json` file** under each sampled ticket's dir in the clone. With\n   `REBAR_TRACKER_DIR`=clone (wins verbatim â€” `config.py:116`) and `REBAR_SYNC_PUSH=off`, run\n   `review_plan(tid, sign=False, emit_sidecar=False, force=True)` (`__init__.py:387`). Because\n   `prior_concerns`â†’`latest_review_result` reads `REVIEW_RESULT` files through `tracker_dir` (the\n   clone), the stripped clone makes recall an empty no-op; code grounding still reads the real\n   checkout. The real `.tickets-tracker` branch/origin are untouched.\n\n4. **Plan-text drift control (material fingerprint).** `orchestrator.material_fingerprint`\n   (pass1.py:551) hashes only `{ticket_id, description, file_impact, children}` â€” plan material, not\n   code SHA â€” so a fresh run emits a `material_fingerprint` comparable to the frozen baseline's. A\n   ticket enters the matrix / FP-control **only if its fresh-run material fingerprint equals the frozen\n   baseline material fingerprint** (the clone's current text == the historically reviewed text).\n   Mismatches (post-close text drift) are excluded and counted. See the validity guard in def 8.\n\n**The replay (candidate side, both tiers).** Drive the candidate branch build's gate over the sample\nvia the recall-stripped clone mechanism (def 3), capturing each returned verdict dict â€” `verdict`,\n`material_fingerprint`, full `findings[]` â€” to `runs/e3/<candidate>/raw_verdicts.jsonl`, atomic append\nper ticket (checkpoint/resume) with a `len(raw_verdicts) == len(sample)` completion assertion before any\nsummary is written. `harnesses/run_review_*.py` is the batch-driver precedent.\n\n**Precise tier â€” fresh current/main gate.** In addition, run the **current/main** gate the same way\n(recall-stripped clone) over the 30-plan subset, Ã—N=3, to `runs/e3/main/raw_verdicts.jsonl`. The\nFP-control compares candidate-fresh vs current-fresh per ticket; the persisted sidecar is used only to\nSELECT the 30 (baseline verdict == PASS) and to run the drift guard (def 4), never as the comparison\nbaseline here.\n\n**Verdict â†’ matrix mapping (coarse tier).** Cells are `(baseline_verdict, candidate_verdict)` over\n`{PASS,BLOCK}Â²`. A candidate verdict that is INDETERMINATE (LLM outage / mid-run degradation â€” Â§5.1:\n~8% of reviews) or a material-fingerprint mismatch is **excluded** from the matrix and every flip-rate\ndenominator, counted in a separate `excluded` block. Baseline INDETERMINATE rounds never become a\nbaseline (def 2). The matrix is **segmented by `impact_model_version`** (one `plan-v3` segment here).\n\n5. **Primary metric â€” PASSâ†’BLOCK flip rate.** Lives in **`transition_matrix.json`** (not\n   `fp_control.json`): `flip_rate = cells.pass_to_block / (cells.pass_to_pass + cells.pass_to_block)`\n   â€” the false-block rate on plans that legitimately passed and closed cleanly. Epic bar â‰¤ 0.02,\n   recorded per segment and reported with the coarse-tier caveat.\n\n6. **Per-criterion finding delta schema.** `runs/e3/<candidate>/criterion_deltas.jsonl`, one row per\n   **(ticket_id, criterion)** over the union of criteria cited in baseline-surfaced âˆª candidate-surfaced\n   findings, exactly these keys: `ticket_id`, `criterion`, `baseline_surfaced_count`,\n   `candidate_surfaced_count`, `baseline_blocking_count`, `candidate_blocking_count`,\n   `net_surfaced_delta` (candidateâˆ’baseline surfaced), `net_blocking_delta` (candidateâˆ’baseline\n   blocking), `new_norm_ids` (sorted list[str]), `removed_norm_ids` (sorted list[str]). **Join key:**\n   `norm_id` is **COMPUTED**, not read â€” verdict `blocking[]`/`advisory[]` findings carry no `norm_id`\n   key (it exists only in sidecar payloads), so the driver imports\n   `from rebar.llm.plan_review import sidecar` and computes `sidecar.norm_id(f)` for every finding on\n   BOTH sides uniformly (baseline sidecar findings too, for symmetry). This is the reword-tolerant,\n   criterion-scoped fingerprint (`pass1.py:506`), correct because the exact-text `id` differs across\n   builds by construction (sidecar.py:247-257). A rollup `criterion_deltas_summary.json` aggregates the\n   same fields per criterion.\n\n7. **LLM nondeterminism control (precise tier).** The gate has no temperature/seed knob (`LLMConfig`\n   exposes neither; `plan-review-chunking-budget.md` notes default temperature for natural\n   repeat-variance), and adding one is a `src/rebar` change out of scope. So the 30-plan R1 gate is\n   replicated **N=3**: run candidate-fresh Ã—3 and current-fresh Ã—3 over the recall-stripped clones. R1\n   metrics are taken at the **median across the 3 candidate replays** (worst-case also reported). The\n   **null-replay noise floor** is current-vs-current: the median (over the 3 current replays, pairwise)\n   count of plans gaining a new blocking finding between two current-gate runs on identical clone input\n   â€” the gate's intrinsic verdict noise. R1's blocking-flip count is read against this floor.\n   R1 FAIL (mirroring SOTA Â§5/R1): median candidate-vs-current #{plans gaining â‰¥1 new blocking finding}\n   **> 3/30**, OR `new_advisory_median_delta` **> 1**.\n\n   `new_advisory_median_delta` is defined concretely (not a raw count and not a delta-of-medians):\n   per ticket, `new_advisories(t) = | {sidecar.norm_id(f) : f in candidate advisory findings} \\\n   {sidecar.norm_id(f) : f in current-gate advisory findings} |` â€” the count of advisory findings the\n   CANDIDATE surfaced on ticket `t` that the fresh CURRENT gate did NOT (a per-ticket \"rise\" in\n   advisories attributable to the candidate, matched by `norm_id` so rewordings don't inflate it).\n   `new_advisory_median_delta = median over the 30 FP-control tickets of new_advisories(t)`, itself\n   taken at the median across the 3 candidate replays (worst-case also reported). This mirrors SOTA\n   R1(ii)'s \"median new-advisory count rises > 1 per review\"; both R1-FAIL metrics are computed by the\n   golden-tested pure helper in `e3_metrics.py`, and `fp_control.json.new_advisory_median_delta` records\n   the value.\n\n8. **Material-mismatch fallback + FP-control validity guard.** During the N=3 replays a ticket whose\n   fresh-run material fingerprint â‰  its frozen baseline fingerprint (def 4) is excluded from that\n   replay and counted in `mismatch_count`. If **> 20%** of the 30-plan subset mismatches in any replay\n   (`mismatch_count/30 > 0.20`), that FP-control run is **INVALID** and must be re-run after\n   re-freezing the sample (mirrors E2's run-validity guard). The threshold is a pure function\n   `e3_metrics.fp_control_valid(mismatch_count, n=30, max_frac=0.20) -> bool`, golden-tested.\n\n**Candidate-build verification.** Each fresh gate run writes `runs/e3/<label>/manifest.json` capturing\nthe build it actually exercised: `candidate_label`, `code_sha` (`git rev-parse HEAD` of the checkout,\ncaptured by the driver at run time), `impact_model_version` (`sidecar.IMPACT_MODEL_VERSION` from the\nrunning build), and `routing_sha`. `criteria_routing.json` is a PACKAGE RESOURCE, not a repo-root\nfile, so `routing_sha` = `sha256` of the file at its resolved package path,\n`Path(rebar.llm.plan_review.__file__).parent / \"criteria_routing.json\"` (verified present) â€” this\nidentifies the candidate build's ACTIVE routing config, wherever the build is installed. The candidate run and\nthe current/main run write separate manifests (`<candidate>/` and `main/`), so an AC can prove the\ncandidate build differs from main (its rubric edits were genuinely in effect), not that the replay\nsilently ran the installed default.\n\n**Stratified sampling frame (reproducible).** Eligible pool = cleanly-closed rows with a usable\n`plan-v3` baseline round (def 2); `verdict`/`model` (absent from the corpus) recovered by joining each\nticket's frozen baseline round on `ticket_id`. Draw **~200** stratified by\n`(ticket_type Ã— baseline_verdict)`, **proportional** to the pool with a **floor of 5 per non-empty\ncell** (sub-floor cells collapse into the same ticket_type's larger verdict cell), deterministic\n`random.Random(1729).sample(...)` (the repo's existing sampler seed â€” README Â§2 /\n`build_adjudication_corpus.py`). **FP-control 30-subset** = deterministic `random.Random(1729)` draw of\n30 from the `baseline_verdict == PASS` members of the 200-sample (a genuine subset; matches SOTA\n\"PASSed + closed + zero post-claim edits\", guaranteed by cleanly-closed) â†’ `runs/e3/fp_control_sample.jsonl`.\n\n## Scope\n\n- **`docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/harnesses/`**: `replay_candidate.py` (driver: `sample` /\n  `run --candidate <label>` / `run --main` / `analyze --candidate <label>` / `--verify`, incl. clone +\n  REVIEW_RESULT strip + manifest write) and `e3_metrics.py` (pure, LLM-free: `build_matrix`,\n  `criterion_deltas`, `pass_to_block_flip_rate`, `fp_control_eval`, `fp_control_valid`).\n- **`docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e3/`**: committed `sample.jsonl`, `fp_control_sample.jsonl`,\n  `baseline.jsonl`, `main/{raw_verdicts.jsonl, manifest.json}`, and per-candidate\n  `<candidate>/{raw_verdicts.jsonl, manifest.json, transition_matrix.json, criterion_deltas.jsonl,\n  criterion_deltas_summary.json, fp_control.json}`.\n- **`docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/README.md`**: an E3 section documenting the baseline source\n  + chosen round, cleanly-closed filter, recall-strip + fresh-both-gates design, material-fingerprint\n  drift control + 20% validity guard, INDETERMINATE exclusion, the two-tier / nondeterminism / cost\n  story, and the R1 verdict.\n- **`tests/unit/test_e3_metrics.py`**: CI-collectable golden tests for the pure `e3_metrics` functions\n  (incl. `criterion_deltas` norm_id join and `fp_control_valid`) over a tiny fixture.\n- **No `src/rebar` behavior change** â€” E3 is measurement. Candidate rubric/registry edits live on the\n  candidate's own experiment-branch build (operator direction; no overlay/config flag). Live LLM calls\n  are billable and run once per candidate/main by the executor; every proving command below re-derives\n  the summaries **offline** from committed `raw_verdicts.jsonl` + `baseline.jsonl`.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] The ~200 sample and the frozen baseline are committed and reproducible; every sampled row\n  satisfies the cleanly-closed filter, and `baseline.jsonl` carries a `plan-v3` `baseline_verdict âˆˆ\n  {PASS,BLOCK}` + `material_fingerprint` per ticket. Proving:\n  `python docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/harnesses/replay_candidate.py sample --verify` (offline;\n  re-derives sample + baseline, exits non-zero unless byte-identical to committed) then\n  `jq -e 'select(.post_claim_edit_class!=\"none\" or .reopen_count!=0 or .force_close!=false)' docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e3/sample.jsonl | head -c1 | ( ! grep -q . )`\n  and `test $(wc -l < docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e3/fp_control_sample.jsonl) -eq 30`.\n\n- [ ] The verdict-transition matrix is committed, segmented by `impact_model_version`, and internally\n  consistent (row-sum cardinality). Proving:\n  `python docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/harnesses/replay_candidate.py analyze --candidate <label> --verify`\n  (offline; recomputes `transition_matrix.json` from committed `raw_verdicts.jsonl` + `baseline.jsonl`,\n  asserts equality) and\n  `jq -e '.segments[] | (.cells.pass_to_pass + .cells.pass_to_block + .cells.block_to_pass + .cells.block_to_block + .excluded.total) == .observed_total' docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e3/<label>/transition_matrix.json`.\n\n- [ ] The per-criterion finding deltas are committed with the pinned 10-key schema, joined on a\n  COMPUTED `sidecar.norm_id`. Proving:\n  `jq -e 'has(\"ticket_id\") and has(\"criterion\") and has(\"baseline_surfaced_count\") and has(\"candidate_surfaced_count\") and has(\"baseline_blocking_count\") and has(\"candidate_blocking_count\") and has(\"net_surfaced_delta\") and has(\"net_blocking_delta\") and (.new_norm_ids|type==\"array\") and (.removed_norm_ids|type==\"array\")' docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e3/<label>/criterion_deltas.jsonl`\n  and `pytest tests/unit/test_e3_metrics.py -k delta -q` (golden proves `criterion_deltas` computes\n  `sidecar.norm_id(f)` for keyless verdict findings and joins baselineâ†”candidate correctly).\n\n- [ ] The primary PASSâ†’BLOCK flip rate is recorded in `transition_matrix.json` on the PASS-baseline\n  denominator, with the â‰¤0.02 bar. Proving:\n  `jq -e '.segments[] | has(\"flip_rate\") and (.flip_rate|type==\"number\") and (.flip_rate == (.cells.pass_to_block / ((.cells.pass_to_pass + .cells.pass_to_block) | if .==0 then 1 else . end)))' docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e3/<label>/transition_matrix.json`\n  and `pytest tests/unit/test_e3_metrics.py -k flip -q` (golden proves `pass_to_block_flip_rate`).\n\n- [ ] The 30-plan FP-control result is committed from the recall-stripped fresh-BOTH-gates design, with\n  the N=3 replication median, the current-vs-current null floor, the material-mismatch validity guard,\n  and the R1 pass/fail decision. Proving:\n  `jq -e '(.replays|length==3) and has(\"new_blocking_median\") and has(\"new_advisory_median_delta\") and has(\"null_floor_pass_to_block\") and has(\"mismatch_count\") and has(\"fp_control_valid\") and has(\"r1_pass\") and (.r1_pass == ((.new_blocking_median <= 3) and (.new_advisory_median_delta <= 1)))' docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e3/<label>/fp_control.json`\n  and `pytest tests/unit/test_e3_metrics.py -k \"fp_control or valid\" -q` (golden proves `fp_control_eval`\n  and `fp_control_valid` at the >3/30, >1, and 20%-mismatch boundaries).\n\n- [ ] The replay provably exercised the candidate build, not the installed default: each fresh run's\n  manifest records the checkout SHA + build markers, and the candidate build differs from main.\n  Proving:\n  `jq -e 'has(\"candidate_label\") and has(\"code_sha\") and has(\"impact_model_version\") and has(\"routing_sha\")' docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e3/<label>/manifest.json`\n  and\n  `test \"$(jq -r .code_sha docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e3/<label>/manifest.json)\" != \"$(jq -r .code_sha docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e3/main/manifest.json)\"`.\n\n- [ ] The E3 method is documented in `runs/README.md`, covering the baseline source + chosen round, the\n  cleanly-closed filter, the recall-strip + fresh-both-gates design, the material-fingerprint drift\n  control, and the two-tier LLM-nondeterminism/cost story. Proving:\n  `grep -q \"recall\" docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/README.md && grep -q \"material_fingerprint\" docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/README.md && grep -q \"cleanly-closed\" docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/README.md && grep -q \"all_review_results\" docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/README.md`."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784264855408882001,"uuid":"39569efa-5a8e-47c9-8e27-28bb03648c56"}